Aug 15 2009 	Fantastic Experience!!!	This was my first ever trip to Las Vegas and I have to say I am very pleased that we stayed at the Four Queens and on Freemont Street as opposed to being on &quot;The Strip&quot;! The staff we encountered were all very helpful and seemed happy to serve us. When we arrived at the hotel, we gave the desk clerk $20 and asked if there was any possibility of receiving a complimentary upgrade and she gave us a petite suite!! We spent 6 wonderful nights on the 14th floor of the South tower in a room with a king size bed, two sofas and a 32&quot; LCD television for less than $190 including the $20 tip!The room was very clean, spacious, and even had a refrigerator and an in room safe large enough to hold a laptop computer and any other belongings. The bathroom was also spacious and had a long vanity with two sinks. The view from the room overlooked the canopy of Freemont Street, and although we could hear the performances in the evenings, we were able to drown them out watching television. We were only in the room one evening before the performances were over, so the noise really was not an issue. We were in Vegas after all and therefore slept late and stayed out late! Freemont Street is great! It was very nice to be able to walk out onto the street and go from casino to casino without having to worry about traffic or walking in the hot sun during the middle of the day. It was remarkably clean for a large city with so many tourists, we were pleasantly surprised. We found Freemont Street to be much cleaner than &quot;The Strip&quot; from our experience. The food at the hotel was fantastic, as was the service. We also found several buffets in the surrounding casinos that were fantastic, and enjoyed all our meals in the Freemont Street area. The Paradise Buffet was probably our favorite place to eat. We had breakfast, lunch and dinner there during our trip. Most of the restaurants and buffets have really good deals on food. We are blackjack players so we did not play slots except for goofing around a few times. If you are a blackjack player, be sure to ask the pit bosses for complimentary food before leaving the tables because you do not earn comps for food on your cards. Most of the casinos in the Freemont area make you ask for comps and do not offer them on the cards, but a couple do. Also, if you look around the area, you can find casinos that offer 3 to 2 payouts on blackjacks as opposed to the 6 to 5 you find in most of them.There is easy access to &quot;The Strip&quot; via The Deuce (double decker bus) by walking about a block down Freemont to the bus stop. It is only $7 per 24 hour period to ride as much as you like. It took approximately 15 to 20 minutes to get to the strip from the hotel. We spent a day at the strip, went back to the hotel, then returned to the strip that evening to see a show at The Mirage. Freemont Street was more our speed because we did not enjoy the wall to wall people and walking long distances to go between casinos on the strip in 105 degree weather under full sun. The temperature was not that bad, but it dehydrates you quickly so be prepared to take along water.Overall we highly recommend the Four Queens and Freemont Street! We will definitely go there again!!	
Aug 14 2009 	Our New Favorite Downtown Hotel~We Loved It!	My husband and I stayed 4 nights early August. This was our first time staying at the Four Queens. We normally stay at GN, but decided to try somewhere &quot;new&quot;, and we were not disappointed! Check-in on a Thursday morning with no line. We were given a room in the North Tower, 16th floor, with a view of The Strip-perfect! Ruby, the girl at the front desk, was very kind and helpful with any questions we had. The room was fine and recently updated. Others say it is small, but we don't spend a lot of time in the room, so it worked perfectly for us. The room had a digital safe, coffee maker(big plus!), and flat panel tv. Air conditioning worked perfectly throughout our 4 night stay. Clean and comfortable...we were happy with our room! Also, for anybody wondering, there are 2 towers; both sets of elevators are in/very close to the casino...so no long walks. I understand there is no pool, but guests can use the pool across the street at Binion's.We also found the gambling to be the best here, as well. We both play slots/video poker, and also played some Let It Ride. Cocktail service was great, as well as friendly bartenders at the bars. Tip them well...those guys/gals work hard!There was only one small disappointment, which does not reflect on the hotel itself or the hotel/casino staff. We went to breakfast Saturday morning at Magnolia's. We were seated right away. We were brought coffee rather quickly. 25 minutes later, we are still waiting for someone to take our order. It was crowded, but not completely full, by any means. We waited 5 more minutes, and decided 30 minutes was more than enough, and we left. I can't comment on the food, as we never had any, and decided not to go back for the rest of the trip. It seemed to us the staff was rather unorganized. Servers taking orders, and also cleaning tables; seemed a bit odd. Maybe we caught them on an off day, I don't know.Our 4 day stay at the Four Queens was an overall wonderful experience, and we will be booking with them again on our next trip without hesitation! Thanks for reading!	
