Apr 6 2009 	Pass it by	This Hotel failed me in most every way. When I asked them for some kind of compensation for all my trouble, I got NOTHING. Below are the highlights (sometimes paraphrased) of the letter I gave to their director of Operations, Mr Walter Lobeck on 1/12/09 detailing the comedy of errors my stay at the 4 Queens was.Dear Mr Lobeck,I have several issues with the Hotel and the service (or lack thereof) I have received while here. I have been unable to fall asleep or stay asleep for every night I have spent here. I wish to explain why. On Wednesday I checked into room #710. Being on the side of the Hotel near the &quot;Experience&quot; I needed to stay up till midnight, although I wanted to go to sleep two hours earlier. (The experience is the light and sound show that takes place on the hour on the FREMONT ST EXPERIENCE adjacent to the hotel). A lady at the front desk took pity on me and let me switch to room 1211 the following morning. Prior to leaving 710, I took a most unpleasant shower. Seems there is termperature control only on the shower. I was getting pelted by such a strong current (there is no flow control) the shower actually hurt. (two strikes for room 705). The following nights, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday I woke up very early in the morning with a sore throat and covered in sweat. (The room was hot as blazes) On Saturday I realized that dry hot air was blowing in my room early mornings despite the thermostat being set to 50 degrees. Prior to Saturday when I woke the hot air had already turned off. Setting the thermostat to 60 and 55 degrees had not worked. The temperature was closer to 80. Disgusted with the heating system, I called the operator who was kind enough to send &quot;Peter the engineer&quot; to my room. Peter explained to me that this system was originally installed to be used solely for cooling, so in point of fact it did not operate as a thermostat. He told me I needed to set the thermostat to 95 degrees (the maximum setting) to make sure the heat did NOT come on! When I attempted to get Peter to admit this was not normal, he refused. I ushered him out.10 minutes later I realized I had forgotten to tell Peter that the toilet was not flushing completely. I called the operator to get this serviced. 5 minutes later Peter appears and is holding a plunger like a weapon and is accompanied by a security guard. Perhaps he thought I was going to punch him in the nose?! By the way, Peter was wrong about the thermostat stopping the heat blowing when set to 95. Monday morning the heat came on anyway. (The heat is on a timer period).I won't bother you with the story about Cox Internet services lying to me about why I could not get online. I had to go downstairs and get the help of Mr Sayed, the assistant manager before I could get service.Did I mention Friday morning I called about my personal feather pillow having gone missing? I do not believe it was intentionally stolen, but rather mistakenly taken by housekeeping. Despit having spent a half hour with two men from Hotel security, and filling out a form for them, NO ONE has called or contacted me. All I wanted was for someone to find and ask the lady who made up my room if she remembers removing a pillow thinking it defective?I ended by asking Mr Lobek if he took issue with any of the facts in my letter. I don't know as I have not heard from him. Since I paid the bill in full, I guess we are done.Please note this is a Binions Property. Do not expect better service across the street at Binions Casino. I had the chance to speak to a restaurant manager in Binions about the miserable restaurant service, and he explained to me what it was like being in between the union and management during a contract dispute. I advise the public to steer clear of both of these places.	
