Mar 1 2009 	Overall good experience	I stayed at Four Queens 02/23-02/27 and only paid 32.00 per night. We are not high maintenance people and therfore did not expect a lot for the price. We arrived right at checkin time and therefore expected a long line. That was not the case, we were through check in with no problems in minutes. Our room was on the second floor and although the first night it seemed very noisy, the remainder of the week was fine. The room itself needed some maintenance. One of the closet doors did not open. The heater made a constant noise. Also, the water in the tub did not drain. And the lights next to the bed were very hard to turn on. (the switch stuck) We should have asked for another room, however, we are not complainers and did not spend much time in the room. The cleaning staff was very friendly and when we asked for extra coffee there was no problem. We did not eat in the hotel as the line at Magnolias was extremely long during normal dinner hours. Overall we had a good trip. The staff at the hotel was very friendly. My three previous trips to Vegas I stayed on the strip, but I think in the future, I will always be downtown. It is much more reasonable and very easy and cheap to take the Deuce up to the strip.	
Feb 27 2009 	Great for the frugal gambler!	We stayed at this hotel from 02/16-02/19. We booked through Expedia and got the third night free. Check in was fast. We were suprised how nice the hotel looked. We asked for the coupon book and got it. First thing we did was check into the Player's club and received free gifts. Our room was neat and clean - think Comfort inn or Best Western. We ate at Magnolias with the 2 for 1 coupon and it was okay. Our last night we ate at Hugo's which was very expensive and fancy but worth every penny. Fremont street was great. This is a great place to go if you want to make your money last. We had a blast and would definately stay again! I played mostly penny slots and was able to parlay $20 into $380 dollars (even though I poured it all back into the machines - it was fun). Came real close to winning the Foose Mustang! Saw Gordie Brown at the Golden Nugget - he was great. Ate at the Mainstreet buffet - best in town. All in all a great stay!	
Feb 25 2009 	Awesome 1st time on Fremont	We stayed at the 4 Queens Oct 4th thru the 10th. I booked it as part of our flight package through US Air. Compared with booking the flight alone, we got the rooms for literally nothing. I think it came up to around $10 a day if that (that is why we stayed for almost a week).We arrived at 10:30am &amp; decided to try checking in. We were told room would not be ready until 2p. I asked if there were any upgrades available, was told not for free, but for $40 a night we could have a mini suite. Since we had not really paid anything for the rooms I took it.The mini suite was available to check in right away. As one of the previous posters said, yes the hotel is old, yes the walls are a little thin, but I have paid 5 times as much for a room elsewhere &amp; had it be a horrible room. We had a non smoking room &amp; there was no smoke smell in the room at all.The mini suite consisted of a large dresser near the front door of room, a &quot;living room&quot; area with a small desk, a decent size &quot;coffee&quot; table with 2 chairs. A large armoire tv cabinet in the living room area. A small &quot;dining&quot; table &amp; 2 chairs. A large leather couch &amp; king size bed. On the wall next to the bed was the &quot;bar&quot; area. It had a very small sink in it &amp; under the counter was a mini fridge. I will try to attach pics, but I have not done any editing to them, so they may be to large. I try to get a lot of pics for a trip advisor report.The bathroom had a large double sink &amp; a decent bath tub &amp; tiled walls instead of a normal bathtub surround. Nothing overly fancy.We tipped the cleaning woman $5 the first morning &amp; asked for extra towels, later that afternoon we came back up to the room, she found us in the hall &amp; thanked us about 10 times. When we got into the room, she had taken all of our personal bathroom stuff (we had just dumped it on the counter) and arranged it on a towel &amp; we had more towels than we would have needed for the entire week. Tips go a long way &amp; I dont mean just to the cleaning people.Remember, if you have a car, valet parking is free as long as you get a VIP pass from the front desk.We did not take our laptops so I can not comment on the high speed internet. They did have internet Kiosks you can use to print out your boarding passes. I think it cost like $3 for 10 minutes.The room service was unbelievably cheap compared to other places I have stayed. I ordered a 1/2 pound double cheeseburger for under $7 &amp; the &quot;fee&quot; was them including 18% gratuity to the bill.Magnolias was great. $5.95 breakfast specials &amp; $7.95 dinner specials for players club members. The prime rib is only $9.95 if you are not a member. It is not the highest quality of prime rib, but it is only 1 or 2 levels from the top. If you are not in a 5 star $50 plus per steak restaurant, this is the same kind of prime rib you will get elsewhere. And according to all of the staff, the same chefs from Hugos Cellar work at Magnolias.I have never been a big slot player (normally lose everything I put in), but I decided to try my hand at some slots on the first day. Won $50 right off on a nickel wheel of fortune (put in $20), cashed out. While I was waiting for my girlfriend to finish playing her first $20, I got bored &amp; put another $20 in. On my next to the last pull I hit for $255. I was very excited.After this I was hooked. Of course I lost more than I won, but I must admit I won a decent amount at the 4 Queens. Any casino we were at out on the strip, I never won anything. This just goes to show every person is going to have a different experience. Am I saying other people posting about their experience at this same hotel &amp; casino were wrong? No, not at all. We may have different expectations or we may have just lucked out on everything.I also won over a total of $300 at 3 card poker (technically $200 profit).All in all it was a great trip. Would I pay full price for a mini suite? Maybe not. Would I have enjoyed it as much if we had a normal room? Hard to say, we didnt spend a lot of time in the room.I will admit, when we checked out my comps were not as much as I expected (after that first win I played a lot of slots &amp; a decent amount of time at card tables as well as my girlfriend spending a lot of time doing both also), but that may be because we received a different bonus &amp; they felt that was enough compensation (sorry cant talk about it).And if you want to check on your comps, do not wait until the last night you are there. You have to check with a slot host. Their offices are located right next door to the front desk &amp; every time we tried to talk to them, they were not there. We had to have them check our bill after we left &amp; they knocked off some food charges &amp; stuff like that &amp; then mailed us the final receipt.If you want to know more, shoot me a message, I did a detailed report on my personal blog, but I will not post a link to it in an open forum like this. If you have any questions at all, let me know.Sorry if it sounds like I rambling, I am trying to post everything I can think of, in as short of a story as possible.We really enjoyed Fremont &amp; everything downtown. Also I must tell you, if you are thinking about going to the Valley of Fire, do it. Definitely worth the trip.Another plus about staying at 4 Queens. Walgreens is less than 10 minutes away. My girlfriend had forgotten her hairbrush &amp; by the time she was out of the shower, I had already returned from buying a new one.Oh &amp; there is a liquor store less than 5 minutes away. What more could you ask for?	
Feb 25 2009 	4 Queens......far from royalty!! Checked out as soon as we arrived	My fiance and I just got back from Vegas and we originally were supposed to stay at the 4 Queens, but as soon as we opened the door to our rooom...we checked out!! We ended up booking a hotel on the strip (much wiser choice)! The casino is very old and all you smell is smoke when you walk in the entrance. The rooms are very small and not clean. Our view from the room was horrible, all you could see was the framework for the lighting show beneath. The set up of the Freemont Experience might have been a cool concept many years ago, but they need to clean up and modernize things. Overall, we had an amazing trip but it was because we made a quick decision to get out of the 4 Queens!! Believe it or not...you can stay at a nice place on the strip for $60 during the week.	
Feb 23 2009 	Our first stay off the strip	We go to Vegas a couple of times a year and always stay on the strip. We wanted to experience Fremont Street so booked at the Four Queens. Our check in around 2 P.M. was quick. No coupon books were offered to us. We had a room on the fourth floor and could sit in our room have a cocktail and watch the light show. It was really quite enjoyable. We had no problem with Fremont street keeping us awake. We turned on the TV and fell asleep to it. The room itself was small but clean. As stated in other reviews the towels were big and fluffy. The bed was very comfortable. There is a coffee pot in the room. This doesn't take away from the fact the hotel is old. The rooms have been remodeled and are comfortable but you can hear every sound in the hall. The hallways are very narrow and the ceilings low as well. All that being said the room cost us $25.00 for the night. How can you beat that for comfy clean place to stay. The cocktail waitresses were great and seemed to always have a smile on their faces. The machines were dead cold though. Oh well, you can't have it all.We ate a Magnolia's. We have always enjoyed eating there when we left the strip for a day on Fremont. This time however. The meal wasn't as good as it usually is. We will however try it again the next time we are in Vegas.If we stay downtown again we most likely will try The Golden Nugget. The four Queens was OK but would like to try another hotel on Fremont Street.	
Feb 23 2009 	Fun and Friendly at the 4 Queens	My friend and I stayed at the 4 Queens Feb 17-20. I have always stayed on the strip, but last year we took a cab to the Downtown area and we had a blast. So this year we wanted to stay Downtown. We picked the 4 Queens because it is right in the middle of everything on Fremont St, it has great reviews, and the price was right.We took the shuttle from the airport to the 4 Queens. The 4 Queens has a small area for cars to drop people off or drop off for the valet, but it seemed to work. Check in was fast and easy. I requested a room in the south tower on an upper floor. Our room was not cleaned yet (it was only 2pm), but they let us store our luggage in the room. The room was perfect the lady at check in put us in a corner room. I dont think that it was any bigger than other rooms, but we had a view in two directions and only people on one side of us. We dropped our luggage off and went downstairs. The first place we went to was the players club to sign up for our cards. We were given a deck of cards in a metal case and a voucher each for Magnolia's Cafe for two for one entres. I was given an extra voucher as it was my birthday. We went over to Magnolia'a Cafe, but got sidetracked at the Craps table. There was a crowd so I watched for a minute. The table was hopping so I tried my luck. 10 minutes later and $40.00 up we went to the Cafe. There was a small line but we did not have to wait long. The hostess was nice and friendly. Our waitress was really nice and very fast. The food was hot and tasted great. We had no problem using the vouchers and off we went.Fremont st is a great place to watch people. We went down to Mermaids and recieved our beads, played some slots and actually won! I came in here last year and played. We had a great waitress last year. She was still there this year.Later we went back to the 4 Queens. My friend played some roulette while I played a little more craps. We both won a little. The dealers at the 4 Queens are great. They are very helpful. We went back up to our room. It was cleaned, everything looked great. When you walk into the room on the right side is a large closet. On the left side is the bathroom. In the bathroom there is a tub/shower combo. There is a single sink with a large amount of counter space. They had an ice bucket, plastic cups, shampoo, lotion, and a small bar of soap on the counter. There was also a hair dryer unit mounted on the wall. The bathroom itself was very clean. Many of the floor tiles were cracked, but that really did not matter. The towels were fine, not big and fluffy, but you have to remember where you are staying. This is not the Ritz, but it is very nice.In the room there is a place to put your suitcase. There is also a stand for the flat screen TV that has 4 drawers under the TV. Next to the stand is the desk and chair. We had two queen beds in the room and between them was a small nightstand with a safe. The bedding was not old or new and looked nice. The blankets are thinner than mine at home, but that was easy to remedy, I called and asked for another and it was brought to me within 10 minutes. Overall the room was very comfortable, the views were great and where we were in the South Tower it was quiet. There was no noise from the Fremont St Experience at all.The next day we spent on the strip. It was busy, but not as busy as when I was in Las Vegas last year. There were specials everywhere on food, drink, shows, nightclubs, rooms, etc. Happy hours specials being run all day. We walked from Mandalay Bay all the way to the Sahara. Took all day as we stopped everywhere.That evening we had dinner at Magnolia's Cafe. We had a different waitress, but she was just as great as our first waitress. My friend had the prime rib special, $7.95 with the players card, and I had the lasagna. We both had the salad, when my friend asked for extra croutons they were brought right away. Both dishes were perfect. My friend loved the prime rib, it came with veggies and a potato.Check out was very easy, we had no problems.I would definatly stay at the 4 Queens again.	
