May 4 2008 	Great Value for the Money	My husband and I recently stayed four nights at the Four Queens. We love staying in downtown Las Vegas and have stayed at several other properties. The room at the Four Queens was comparable to some of the others. However, if you are looking for the upscale quality of the &quot;mega&quot; resorts, this is probably not the place for you. The room was average. I loved the coffee pot in the room. Surprisingly, the bed was one of the most comfortable hotel beds I've ever slept in. The fan to the air conditioning was pretty noisy. You would have to turn up the volume on the TV when the A/C came on. One complaint I had was that the selection of television channels was pretty limited. There were no movies channels like HBO. I became ill and had to spend one whole day in the room. I had to watch CNN or sports most of the day. The staff at the Four Queens was great. Everyone we encountered was very friendly. The pit crew and dealers were nice. (Thanks Robb and Mr. IL). The front desk staff were very quick at check in. The valets were very polite and efficient.We had a great breakfast at Magnolia's. You get a great deal on breakfast with your players card. It's $4.95 for a huge breakfast including coffee. The food was good. We also had a sandwich from the deli. It was really good but a bit pricey. For sandwiches, chips and drinks for two people it was almost $20.My husband and I have decided we will be staying at Four Queens again. It is a great value for the price.	
May 2 2008 	Great Experience!	Our first experience at the Four Queens won't be our last. We had a great time while in Las Vegas thanks to the staff and Management of this great hotel. Our Non Smoking room was clean every day and never had an odor of prior sneaky smokers. The price was right from Saturday through Wednesday and the atmosphere was exactly what we had come to expect from previous experience staying downtown. There were $5 Craps and Blackjack tables most of the time if not all of the time. (I usually gamble in the early morning hours after the late night crowds have left) The Roulette tables had some of the best minimums in Downtown. PaiGow minimum was $10 most of our visit. I don't know how loose the slots were since I seldom play them unless I am killing time. Our 8th floor hotel room door was about 50 feet from the Elevator (North Tower) and maybe another 30 to the Freemont St. Experience once you step off the elevator. We had drinks several times late in the evening at the Chicago Brewing Company while we played Video Poker. Overall, we found the bartenders, wait staff, dealers, and front desk personnel to be very polite and courteous. In the future I will contact the Hotel directly for reservations because of a goof up by Travelocity who ended up having to resend our confirmed reservation via Fax. ( I had called the day earlier to confirm our reservations at the hotel) I'm glad I did. I will recommend the Four Queens to my friends because it is right in the middle of downtown, has a great covered parking area which is free for guests, and because of it's value.	
