Mar 9 2008 	Great Downtown Hotel	We loved this hotel and its central downtown location which is perfect for seeing the Fremont Street Experience. There is only a short walk from the parking garage to the check-in desk, and then to a room. The parking is free to hotel guests, with a validation given at check-in. We don't agree about the small room size we have read about in other reviews, our room with two beds was of average size and although the bath was smallish it was well laid out. The hotel was tastefully renovated in 2007, it was very clean and new-looking and the beds were comfortable. Unlike many Las Vegas hotels, our room had a coffee maker and a flat screen TV. We liked the many reasonably-priced food choices within the hotel. Don't stay here if you want to be on the strip, because the downtown is a different area. We like both, and we usually divide our visit between a strip hotel and a downtown hotel because both areas have a lot to offer.	
Mar 6 2008 	Great comfortable room in heart of downtown Vegas	Clean, comfortable, safe, and centrally located for the Fremont Street scene, the Four Queens is a smart choice for anyone looking for an affordable casino hotel. Housekeeping is conscientious and the newer furnishings include 32&quot; HD televisions. It's funny to think of a 200-room hotel as &quot;small&quot; but the Four Queens felt cozier than the other gargantuan casino properties. It's next door to the Golden Nugget and across the street from Binion's Horseshoe, so there's plenty of action nearby. I used to visit Las Vegas frequently twelve years ago, and back then I would stay at the Stardust because it offered me the same combination of affordability and amenities. Sadly, the Stardust is now gone and the enormous super-casinos are rapidly devouring the Strip. Downtown has changed little, so I appreciate the nostalgia and authenticity of Fremont Street. I'll make a return trip to the Four Queens.	
