Feb 14 2008 	OK but noisy 	Although the staff members were all very courteous, our stay at the Four Queens was frustrating in a few ways. For one thing, many of the hotel's rooms face Fremont Street, which features loud bursts of music every half hour between 7 p.m. and midnight, every night. If you are an early to bed type or are bringing young children, either request a room that is as far from Fremont Street as possible, or just don't stay at this hotel. In addition to the noise, downsides included the fact that you have to weave through the incredibly smoky casino to get to the hotel's restaurants; the fact that there is no pool or hot tub or anything at all to do at the hotel if you want to take a break from gambling; and the fact that after we moved to a new room, the tub faucet leaked all night and the room smelled of smoke even though it was a non-smoking room. On the plus side, their Magnolia's restaurant had good food, and the light show at the Fremont Street Experience is fun.A big issue to consider is the general location of the hotel. If you aren't familiar with Vegas, please note that the Four Queens is nowhere near the more famous and fabulous hotel/casinos such as the Bellagio, Venetian, Luxor, and Paris. To get to them, either you need a car or you jam yourself onto a city bus called the Deuce, which can take 40-50 minutes to get to the newer casinos at rush hour and can be standing-room-only crowded.If all you want from your stay is to gamble and smoke cigarettes all day, this hotel will probably be fine for you. If not, you are better off staying at one of the newer casinos on the newer end of the Strip. They are less smoky and have a lot more to see and do than the Four Queens.	
Feb 14 2008 	Nice Stay on Freemont	This is my third stay on Freemont Street in two months and it was a nice experience. The room was small but very clean with a nice flat screen tv. Yes I sometimes watch sports that I bet on in the room and rest. The Sportsbook is small but very friendly. After it closes you can cash your tickets at the Cashier of the Casino. They do not have a poker room,but just across the street at Golden Nugget there is a nice one. The only complaint was the hot water was not the greatest,but the stay was worth the money. Compared to the Plaza at the same price range,it was much better.	
Feb 13 2008 	Decent location helpful staff	If this hotel were anywhere else, it would be pretty good. Hence my four star rating. The rooms are clean, the staff is helpful, the parking is free, and the location is convenient in its way. The nastiest drawback is that rooms that are next to Fremont Street have all the noise of the Fremont Street Experience. Otherwise a well run hotel.However, it's in a bad location for Vegasunless you want to be downtown. I did, my wife didn't. She thought the hotel was pretty average. Either way, I'm not sure it merits the $95/night average room rate. Bottom line: if you turn in early make sure you are far from Fremont Street or you won't sleep before midnight. Make sure you score a good deal, because it's not that much better than a Day's Inn.	
