Feb 10 2008 	A great stay under the canopy	We just arrived home after a &quot;great&quot; stay at the 4Queens for 4 nights in room 408-North Tower. It seemed the even number rooms faced Fremont St. We requested 2 queen beds that were under the canopy so we could enjoy the light show and people watch from our room, in the short time that we &quot;expected&quot; to be in it and that's exactly what we got. Early check-in was not an issue and the staff was great.The elevator for the North Tower was 20 steps away (I counted for this review) from Fremont St and our room from the elevator was the same distance. Great!!The room was &quot;very&quot; clean and the beds-pillows were &quot;too&quot; comfortable because when we layed down for a quick nap at 8pm (after a long plane ride in), we slept the night away until 5am. Grrrrr! FSE did not keep us awake nor was the noise from it disturbing. Actually, it was great to just lay in bed and watch it before our, so called.... 9 hr nap. With the window closed (it opens about 6 inches for fresh air), the music etc was not an issue.The room contained a 3 cup coffee maker with all the fixings but we did bring our own coffee, filters etc so we could enjoy coffee the way we like it. According to a wall sign...Ice machines are on floors 4-9-10-12-18-19. Soda($2 for 20oz) machines are on 4-5-8-11-15-17The bathroom contained the usual shampoo, lotion and hand soap. Not a large bathroom, but suited us just fine.Housekeeping was great and did not bother us while we had the &quot;do not disturb&quot; sign on the door.The gift shop closes early but Walgreens is a short block away for anything that you need....meds, snacks, drinks etc.The &quot;only&quot; complaint we had was the casino was too hot to enjoy when the casino got busy at night, even though the outside temps were in the mid 40's, so we ended up playing mostly at the Fremont Casino across the street at night. Great buffet at the Fremont and enjoyed two meals there with 2-4-1 vouchers given for our meager slot play. The Fremont will soon open up a Dunkin Donuts for northeners or us ex-northeners to enjoy...yea!!!Our stay, booked thru their web-site was at a cost of $49-$49-$49-$99-Tues thru Sat but cheaper rates were advertised a week before check-in so watch your rates before you go. I hope I covered all questions and think you'll also enjoy it if you don't expect the costly suites found on the strip. We'll definitely stay at this hotel again.	
