Jan 5 2008 	A pleasant surprise	I just returned from a solo trip this Jan and wanted something econimical and clean. I booked the four queens for 33.95/night week day rate after reading some of the other reviews here and was pleasantly surprised. Checked in early at 1130 am, no problem, king room # 1816 overlooking the top of the fremont canopy. Very clean, new furnishings, carpet, lcd flat panel widescreen tv. The room comes equipped with a coffee maker, iron and board, hair dryer but no mini bar. I had no issues with noise either from the hall or from next door. The staff throughout the casino/hotel were attentive and friendly. I did not try Hugo's Cellar but Magnolia's for breakfast at 6.95 was good.  This is a wise choice if you're looking for clean and comfortable accomodations downtown.	
Jan 3 2008 	Not bad for 2 stars	I stayed here for just one night unexpectedly. We had reservations at the Venetian hotel on the strip but I arrived in Vegas one day early, so I got a priceline deal at the Four Queens. Overall I have to say it wasn't too bad. The rooms were much better than I had expected for a 2 star place - they were very clean, comfy beds, good service etc. The hotel was a bit old and rundown. There were many signs of neglect as well - the ice machine in my hallway was overrun with water and sludge which had seeped into the carpet. Aside from that - the main downside was the location of the hotel. If you're into the older buildings and vintage vegas than this might be your dream place. I have to admit that I did not feel safe walking outside the hotel at night (or much less any time of the day). BTW - there isn't much that makes me nervous or feel unsafe, since I grew up in Baltimore and now live in downtown DC. Keep in mind that the Four Queens is a very different vegas experience than one gets while staying on the main strip. Aside from not feeling as safe - I noticed a large number of vagrants, homless people and drunks in the &quot;freemont street&quot; area. The whole area around the Four Queens also had a strange earieness to it - like an old vintage carnival horror movie with run down buildings, blinking ligts that stopped working decades ago and the heavy stench of dank cigars.Overall - it's certainly a memorable experience staying at the Four Queens. From my experience - you'll be treated well by the staff and you won't be disappointed by your room - but it might be worth spending a few extra bucks to stay at a classier, safer place.	
