Aug 5 2007	Our room was burglarized and I'm sure it was an inside job.	I stayed with some friends at the 4 Queens. While there, our room was burglarized, and items stolen included a brand new laptop, new model BlackBerry, expensive sunglasses, and other items. It's a long story, but the pattern of what was taken and what was not taken led us to believe very strongly that it was an inside job, and that our room was actually cased the day before the burglary to prepare for the theft.Afterward, the hotel could not possibly have been less responsive or considerate - they did not even offer us a discount on the room (actually, I can't even recall an apology), and as far as we can tell, performed no investigation whatsoever regarding the theft - their only communication was to say they were not responsible, and I never even got so much as a follow up call from the manager or anyone else. Even if you didn't think it was an inside job, what does it say about the place that the hotel does not even care enough to follow up, let alone offer a discount or anything else you might expect, when people have thousands of dollars of goods stolen out of a locked room?If you value your possessions in the least, or decent customer service, I would strenuously advise against ever staying at the 4 Queens for any reason.	
Jul 23 2007 	You Must Try The Four Queens!	We stayed at the Four Queens July 17 &amp; 18th in the South Tower. My parents stayed in an adjoining room. Our rooms were 545 &amp; 547, both non-smoking with two beds per room. My 80-yr-old mother has stayed in the FQ about five times over the years, and the last time was 10 years ago. She has always said how she loves the Four Queens! After reading the reviews here, I was apprehensive about the quality of the rooms, and the hotel as a whole. I didnt know what to expect, since everyones idea of quality is so varied. I myself tend to be somewhat picky. Since my parents wanted to stay at the FQ because thats where weve always stayed, I agreed to stay there. I can say with all honesty - I am so glad that I did! Our rooms were more than reasonably priced. The rooms were very clean and sparkling. I saw nothing dirty about anything that I used or looked at. Yes, it is an older-type hotel and rooms, but it is elegant too. The place has personality. I wasnt exceptionally impressed with the registration desk clerks. They were not rude, but they were non-smiling, unfriendly and aloof. And it wasnt that busy at the FQ during the week. Also during check-out, our desk clerk did not even mention that if we had a Players Club card (we did), that we should check with the Players Club Host to see if we may be able to comp our rooms (we were able to comp both nights and had a free stay at FQ). Had I not read it at this website, I would not have known to do it. The room had a new flat-screen T.V., which I only watched a little. The air conditioner kicked tailfeathers and kept the room cool since it was 114 degrees outside. Our rooms looked out over the hotel canopy and partially over the Fremont Experience. Music started around 8 p.m. and stopped at 12 a.m. Who the heck is in their room sleeping at Midnight while visiting Las Vegas anyway? Take handy-dandy foam earplugs with you if you have a doubt. The casino was active and nice and had plenty of modern, fun slot machines, and was comparable to other casinos as far as variety and pay-offs. We ate at Magnolias Restaurant, and to me  the food was just so-so. I wish wed ventured out to places to eat outside of FQ, but didnt to save time. We did not try Hugos Cellar. Acting on the advice of other reviewers, I tried the Deuce (double-decker bus) to travel from the FQ in Old Vegas to The Strip. There is a lot more to traveling that way than meets the eye. Reviewers had described it as a convenient way to get around. I did not find that to be true. As a not-so-physically-fit 50-Something, to have to walk the distance from the FQ to the Deuce depot to catch the bus in the blazing heat of the late morning was almost unbearable. It was much further than described by an FQ employee. Once I arrived, I had to stand in a long line of others waiting to board in the heat. I was so glad that my mother had decided not to join me, as she would not have been able to withstand it. I did buy the $5 all day pass as I wanted to visit various places along the Strip. It is $2 each time you board if you dont have the pass. The Deuce was cramped, crowded and slow. From the beginning boarding, to the final boarding, and the times in-between, it was the same. The seats were all full and people were standing in the aisles jammed together like sardines as the Deuce inched its way along the strip. Folks, this was during a weekday! One time I was standing at one of the stops to board, and there were so many people waiting to board, the bus stopped and took on about 4 people and pulled off. The remainder of us had to wait in the heat until the next bus came along and there was pushing and shoving to get on the next one. My return trip back to the Four Queens from MGM Grand took at least an hour. The only other option is to take a taxi. I believe if I go to Vegas again, I may opt for the taxi. The Four Queens may not be a 5-Star hotel like some of the newer ones, but it is certainly worth more than the charge to stay there. If I get the chance to go to Vegas again, I would definitely stay at the FQ. So should you. You wont be disappointed.	
