Jul 21 2007	Great Show Great Price!(Reprise)	I stayed at the 4Q with my wife and daughter from 2 July to 9 July, 2007. This review is a continuation of my 4Q review of the same title from July, 2006.Just as last year, I totally enjoyed the Four Queens. The entire hotel is clean and well-staffed; the location is perfect.Here are my detailed tips and updates:1. Check-in was SO quick! No lines, early check-in OK. I requested a North Tower room and tipped at registration to get the kind of room I wanted.2. You can watch the Fremont Street Experience shows from your window, if you request an even-numbered room on the 4th, 5th, or 6th floor. The FSE shows ran at 8:30, 9, 10, 11, and midnight each night.3. There was no evidence of slow elevators. Last year, I frequently saw impatient South Tower visitors; I never saw any frustration about elevators at the 4Queens this year.4. All rooms have new flat-screen TVs. Cool! You can watch the keno draw on one channel, and another channel has gambling instructional videos.5. I never saw any $2 minimum blackjack tables, as I did last year. Tables were always $5 minimum.6. There were LOTS of full-pay Jacks or Better video poker machines. You really have to look, because most of the machines are newer and play multiple games. The &quot;Deuces Wild&quot; machines offer Full-Pay Jacks-or-Better; these are 4-5 rows west of the craps tables. This is not a small issue; it is 100% average payback, even if you are playing nickels!!7. There is another bank of eight full-pay machines right behind the keno parlor/sports book. These seem to be well-known, as they are often full. However, the keno board above these machines is the one broadcast on the hotel's keno channel; you can stand up and WAVE to everybody on TV! 8. Sports book closes at night? Wow. That is not good. When they ARE open, though, the attendants are very helpful and fun!9. Magnolia's Restaurant is VERY nice. Your 4Q slot club card saves you up to 45%, especially at breakfast. I did not visit Hugo's Cellar.10. There is no pool, but you can usually walk into the Golden Nugget pool area and shark tank.11. Parking was free with the VIP card you get at check-in. The parking garage is small, though: on weekends, the self-parking may fill. I use Valet parking on Fri/Sat nights; a $2-$3 tip gets your car fast enough.12. Don't miss the shows &amp; events downtown. The spray-paint artists are still there, but the lady who writes on rice grains was gone. There is usually live music between 4Q and the Fitz; there is usually a pianist between Golden Gate and Vegas Club each night.13. Do NOT let the timeshare sellers soak up your precious LV time. Tell them you are headed out to catch your flight. They'll back off.14. I love the small Four Queens pens that are on the writing tables. Yes...I took one...I now have three of these flat pens.15. If you must go to the strip, take the parallel Industrial Road to save time.My family was impressed with 4Q again. We will stay there again next time. It only takes one glance at 50-100 desperate travelers in a check-in line at Circus Circus or Luxor, to remind you about he value of stayong downtown. Let the others pay $250 per night on the Strip.Put &quot;Las Vegas&quot; in the subject line of an e-mail, if you need details.Gene Padgett! (DrGPadgett@nctv.com)	
