Jul 3 2007	Fine room; bargain price; nice staff!	When choosing a hotel in Las Vegas, it's important to consider what is important to you. If, for instance, you are not satisfied unless your bathroom is huge, made of marble, and equipped with a phone by the toilet, then don't stay at Four Queens. Similarly, don't stay there if you need 25000 thread count sheets and beds that are fit for Diamond Jim Brady. If that stuff is more your style, run, don't walk, to places like Bellagio, THE Hotel, and The Venetian. And bring a great deal of cash and your best posing clothes while you're at it.If, however, you are looking for a clean, abeit small room to lay your head for a couple of nights, and don't mind staying Downtown as opposed to The Strip, I found Four Queens to be excellent, and a superb value as well.My friend and I had a very good experience, starting with the price, which totaled $200 for three nights, including Friday and Saturday night, when Vegas hotels siphon money at the same rate as Keno. For that $200, we had NO WAIT at check in, and the woman who checked us in was kind, courteous, and even let us check in a couple of hours early. When I visited Paris to gamble the next day, I saw throngs of frustrated tourists waiting to check in...and probably paying triple the price.Yes, the room is fairly small, and yes, the decor is dated. But the room was immaculate, there was a plasma TV, and the bed was fine. Think about it: when you are sleeping, do you really notice how expensive the mattress is?The room was quiet, though to be fair, that may have had as much to do with who our neighbors were as anything else. We had a splendid view of a parking garage, but when in Vegas, the only time I stare out the window is to bemoan my blackjack losses. So for that, a parking garage seems appropriate. None of the noise from the hectic Fremont Street leaked into our room, but then again, that may have had as much to do with our room placement as anything else.The casino was friendly and accommodating, with plenty of cheap tables, even on the weekend. Plus, about 10 other casinos (literally) are within walking distance, and Golden Nugget is right across the street. If you really like to gamble and jump from casino to casino, Downtown has The Strip beat hands down. The crowd certainly is older and more &quot;middle class&quot; than down the road, but again, it's what you value in your Vegas trip. In addition, joining the players' club was a snap, and was given a free deck of cards for doing so, which not one other casino club did. Parking cost $3 a day, which I was more than willing to pay considering what our room cost.To sum: If you want a clean, comfortable room with a very accommodating staff at a bargain rate, Four Queens just might be King of Downtown.	
