Sep 5 2006 	The only good thing was the food	We reserved a non-smoking room. My husband is allergic to cigarette smoke. Upon arrival we were told that there were no non smoking rooms left but there was one smoking room available that had recently been remodeled. They would move us to nonsmoking the following morning. The first room had nice decor, was a comfy room overall, but it still smelled of stale cigarette smoke. We would have happily stayed in that room if the smell had not been there.They moved us to a nonsmoking room after being reminded that they needed to do so the next night and the bed in the second room honestly felt like two box springs on top of each other. We asked to be moved and were told they had rented out all the other nonsmoking rooms. We asked if the mattress could be switched out (another employee had told us 4Q was renovating all the rooms and new mattresses were available, all we had to do was ask) and were at first told this would be no problem. Got to the room to wait for the new matress and were then told that this could not be done because &quot;only engineers are qualified to do that&quot;. We complained again and miraculously they found us another nonsmoking room with a bed that was not quite so bad but still both of us woke up with aches and pains. There were holes in the towels, sheets, and pillowcases as well in the third room. There were also gouges in the drywall of the room and lukewarm water. The staff acted like they could have cared less for the most part about any of our concerns. Also, don't fall for the time share people in the lobby. We were told that if we went on their sales pitch tour we would get sixty dollars cash. We were thinking of getting a time share eventually anyway so this sounded pretty good to us. And it was a free trip around Vegas so why not! The voucher we received was not redeemable for cash, hotel credit only. When we complained to the supervisor he seriously rolled his eyes at my husband. We ended up using the voucher to eat at Magnolia's, the 24 hour restaurant inside the very smoky casino (they have a glass wall seperating the casino from part of the nonsmoking section), and had a great meal. Service in the restaurant was wonderful too. We also tried the pizza place and really liked the food there. I would some it up as poor customer service in a run- down hotel. Their slogan is &quot;The class of Downtown&quot; but we sure didn't see that at all. They need to start renovating at warp speed or change their slogan. Either way we won't be back.	
Sep 5 2006 	Would not recommend	To begin with, the hotel is far from a 3 star. At the most it is a 2 star. Second, the hotel is run down and old. Needs to be either torn down or renovated. Rust stains in shower, cracked tiles in the bathroom, hair in the sink, carpet was stained, are just a few of the features we found not so desirable. We were given an adjoining room with noisy neighbors that felt it was ok to smoke on the non-smoking floor. It was so bad by the 3rd night of our trip that the smoke was seeping underneath the adjoining door and was making our room hazy. When the front desk was notified, they simply let us know that they could not tell people what to do in their rooms. That was absurd. Upon checkout, we asked for a manager and notified him about our complaint, but we were blown off as well. We let him kindly know that we would not be staying at their hotel in the future. Point is, if you ask for non-smoking at any establishment, if someone lights up a smoke next to you in the non-smoking section, they will be asked to put it out, after all, it is the non-smoking section. Apparently, this hotel does not see it that way.	
Jul 22 2006	Not good	This hotel is not good at all. The bed is dirty, and the bathroom is bad. We used to leave tips at every hotel, but this one, no way!	
Jul 17 2006	Satisfactory Room for the Price Great Location	Compared to some of the reviews I've read, I want to give this hotel five stars for beating my low expectations--let's face it, I was a little frightened after Hotwire revealed the name of the hotel. but don't believe the bad reviews. I stayed in the North Tower, on the 8th floor- exactly level with the &quot;fremont experience.&quot; I don't know what noise people were complaining of- it was fine. and the lights were pretty through the sheers, and completely hidden when the heavy curtains were pulled. The room was clean, the furnishings not fashionable but decent and in good repair, and the linens were surprisingly soft, great pillows even. The staff were friendly and kind, and I even had a housekeeper interrupt me from returning to my room after brunch to warn me that she hadn't straightened my room yet, and would I like her to do it now.... The place is NOT a three star, probably a 2.5. The Days Inn comes to mind. And the only thing the TV is good for is for puchasing videos- it can do nothing else. but unless you're staying at the Nugget (was sold out) what else might you expect downtown? it's not posh, but it's a Vegas experience for a bargain. Further, you can take the Deuce ($2 double decker bus) down to the Strip- which CAN take forever in traffic, but good views along the way- which is all of a 3-4 minute walk from the hotel front door, THROUGH the Fremont experience. If you haven't been, picture an outdoor shopping outlet with panels way aloft that provide the show in the evening but provide reasonable shade during the day--there are speakers playing a variety of music mounted on posts every 50 feet or so, and as you walk what is essentially a pedestrian mall between the casinos, you'll run into street performers (artists and the like) and vendors of every touristy/mall sort. and don't forget the guys selling cocktails on the street- big plastic yard-long margaritas. So the woman who wrote that you get to the bus through a scary part of town clearly got lost. (how?) Magnolia's is not what people have made it out to be, but prime rib for $6- edible. The breakfast was much better. All in all, so much better than I had anticipated. And perhaps one of the BEST parts about the hotel room? I requested a non-smoking room and I got it. No trace of the scent to be found, and that IS a sticking point with me. I am pleased with my experience overall and wanted to set the record straight, because the 4 Queens is getting a reputation it doesn't deserve.	
Jul 16 2006	Good Value Nice Staff	I really enjoyed my stay at the Four Queens. My husband plays there from time to time, but not really that much, and we got three nights free and the fourth for $24 by calling and asking what we could get on his player's card. The staff were nice and efficient, the dealers at the blackjack tables were particularly friendly (they swung my husband a free meal at Magnolia's, about a $50 value, despite play that was lower than required for that comp).The rooms are at about a 2-1/2 star level, clean, few have views worth looking at, and are some of the only rooms in Vegas with coffee makers. Having a 1/2 price ticket booth in the lobby is a plus and is centrally located downtown. I'm looking forward to my next stay here.	
