Apr 10 2005	Good Location-A Great Deal	We were guests of the Four Queens exactly 7 years ago today. Last minute change to plans-most hotels we wanted were sold out or WAY too expensive...thought we should give this a try. A LONG day of travelling (delays, bad turbulance, etc) and a late check in later, we arrived in our room to find it dirty. I was exausted...and stressed...and emotional...so dear hubby to be calls to front desk. They send someone up, and they upgrade us to a Fremont Street - facing suite. Decor outdated, sure. But it made my day. Casino nice enough-at the time I was all about the blackjack and I found a dealer who I LOVED. Funny, fast, knowledgeable...kept us all interested, laughing, and most importantly for the casino...at the table! I wish I could remember his name, but I do remember that my hubby kept borrowing money from me when he was down...and every time he would win a few hands, the dealer would stop, tell him to give me my &quot;loan&quot; back, and say &quot;No Money...No Honey.&quot; The Four Queens has its good and not so good points. But it is a decent value for those who go for the experience and the sightseeing...not to spend their money on a room alone. We've stayed there a few times, and we've stayed other places too. Would recommend and would go back again.	
Mar 30 2005	Better than I expected	Weekend of March 18, lots going on in Vegas and even a couple months early stuff the quality of Treasure Island or Stratosphere was 250, sometimes more. Hotwire had a 4 star (they always over &quot;star&quot;) for 85.00. Figured it was the nicer GOlden Nugget so I bit. Early check in was fine, nice young man and got my key. North tower is right off the casino, very convenient for gambling. Facing away from Fremont on the 8th floor wasn't very noisy at all. Clean room with all the basics, good housekeeping. Casino was okay, had the prime rib special in the restaurant and it was lame. Still, a far better experience than say the San Remo. No pool, but might not have used it any way.	
Mar 30 2005 	Four Queens Great Experience!	Really great price- around $30 per night. Upon request, you can stay on the top floor and get a great view of the desert. The food in the casino is not the best, we ate at the Chicago style pizza-- it was just ok. Their microbrewery is just ok as well, neither I nor my spouse were fans of their beers. For you money, go to the Fremont Casino's buffet across the street-- the best buffet we found at Vegas!The room was clean and the staff was relatively friendly (keep in mind that the staff in Las Vegas are somewhat jaded no matter where you stay!) Yes the rooms are a little noisy-- but that's only if you go to sleep before midnight! The only complaint I have is that the room service clean up is really slow. The same plates sat outside the hotel room for 4 nights! But you can't expect everything to be perfect at this price! Also, there is no pool, or transportation from the airport. But once again, what can you expect at this price??	
