Feb 24 2005	Four Queens ain't Four Stars but...	The title of this review may suggest that the Four Queens was inadequate but truthfully, I enjoyed my experience in Vegas...especially the Dowtown/Fremont area. If you have never been to Las Vegas (and before going with my girlfriend in August, we had never been either) you will undoubtedly be encouraged to stay on the Strip. That is for good reason. The Strip is as amazing as you have heard about and probably more...still, when we arrived we had no idea if staying Downtown was a good or bad thing. Instead of just simple narrative, I will break down the Four Queens, my trip and Vegas in general like this, LOCATION:We arrrived at the Four Queens on a Friday night and were immediately in wonder of the bright, vibrant lighting. The Four Queens is located in the heart of the Fremont Experience, adjacent to the Golden Nugget and Binion's Horseshoe. The Fremont Experience is a collection of gaming, restaurants, shopping and entertainment in Downtown Vegas, approx. two miles from the Strip. We had heard complaints about getting to and from the strip but honestly, the inexpensive bus ride is no more than ten minutes and most of that time is because of stops and rediculous traffic. No problem really. People will say that staying on the Strip is the thing to do but we didn't mind the back and forth travel. In fact many people we talked to on the Strip never made it Downtown, so we felt we got the best of both worlds. ACCOMODATIONS:The Four Queens is definitely &quot;old-school&quot; Vegas. We stayed in a standard room on a high level floor. The room was seemingly stuck in 70's decor but it was clean and not tiny. The ceiling in the shower had a tinge of rust, which I didn't care about but my girlfriend was not pleased. Our view was relatively bland, however, the mountains in the distance were beautiful. Because we spent very little actual time in the room, I can't tell you what room service is like. I can tell you the restaurant in the casino is good. And for that matter the casino itself was cool. (A lot of people we talked to at the tables and slots were staying at other hotels) Overall, I have nothing bad to say about the room, staff or casino. In fact, we when I broke down the price of the package, our nightly rate for hotel was approx. $16!! Can you really go wrong? And furthermore, what would you expect?WHAT ELSE:The Four Queens was nothing spectacular but it was not bad at all. When you visit the hotels on the Strip you will be blown away at the lavish designs and over-the-top construction. Beautiful giants such as the Bellaggio, Mandalay Bay and Ceasar's Palace are so plush, places like the Four Queens appear drab and pathetic. Still, because the location was downtown away from the madness of the Strip, the Four Queens is a reasonable, low-maintenance option for those who are the chill, low-maitenance type.	
Jan 30 2005	Thumbs down to the casino staff.	I did not stay in this hotel, but I did visit its casino on the night I ventured downtown. The whole experience left a bad taste in my mouth, and I will not return to the casino or the hotel again.A slot machine malfunctioned. I was attempting to press the &quot;select lines&quot; button on the screen, but the touchscreen was mis-aligned, and pressing the &quot;select lines&quot; button actually equated to a press of the &quot;Max Bet&quot; button -- something I most certainly didn't want to do. I immediately stopped and had a friend watch my machine while I attempted to located a slot attendant. Not seeing one, I asked the nearest employee - a security guard. &quot;Excuse me -- are there any slot attendants floating around here?&quot; He replied rather gruffly, &quot;I don't know.&quot; I, now peeved, replied, &quot;Do you work here?&quot; He replied, &quot;Yeah, but not in that department.&quot; Thanks, buddy.I walked to a different part of the casino and located a slot attendant. She walked over to the machine, I explained the problem, and then she pressed the &quot;select lines&quot; button -- the exact same thing happened -- another (unwanted) max bet (now I'm down two max bets on this machine that I was attempting to just play down a couple of credits and cash out with). After a minute, she called her supervisor over. The supervisor came over, but didn't understand what the problem was. She then insisted that I was playing the game wrong and that the machine in fact was not malfunctioning. I even explained that her co-worker had witnessed (and caused) the machine to again malfunction because of the faulty touchscreen -- she didn't understand (or care), and proceeded to press buttons and spin the reels. She finally assured me that I would get my credits back, but because of her lack of understanding the situation, she wound up short-paying me by six credits, despite the fact that I kept insisting the exact amount that I had.As I cashed out at the cage, I asked if there was a business card available for the casino manager. The cashier (the friendliest person I encountered the whole time) was very apologetic and asked if she could help me with anything. I explained the situation, and she said she'd call the slot manager over.The slot manager came over, I got partway through my explanation of what happened when the original supervisor came over. He stopped listening to me and asked her a few questions (to which she basically said, 'he had a problem with the machine and I paid him), asked me exactly what the problem was, to which I replied, &quot;Your machine malfunctioned -- the touchscreen is mis-aligned. She didn't understand or didn't care to understand what the problem was, told me I was playing the machine incorrectly, and then shorted me money paying me.&quot; Once he understood that I was shorted, he offered to pay me the six credits, but at that point I was so sick of the ordeal (and wanted to prove a point) that I told him to please keep the money and just fix the problems (the machine and the staffer). He told me he would, and I left....and that is why I will not visit the Four Queens again, and encourage other people to visit one of the many other fine hotels/casinos in Las Vegas.	
